00:30:22.314 --> 00:30:25.040
And there are studies
that show that,

00:30:25.040 --> 00:30:27.500
contrary to what was
thought at first,

00:30:27.500 --> 00:30:31.360
that there is a
difference between reading

00:30:31.360 --> 00:30:35.150
to somebody with a book,
where you turn pages,

00:30:35.150 --> 00:30:36.480
and reading from a tablet.

00:30:36.480 --> 00:30:39.550
And that the kids interact
with the medium and the written

00:30:39.550 --> 00:30:42.100
word in very, very
different way--

00:30:42.100 --> 00:30:44.720
and probably close
to the way you guys

00:30:44.720 --> 00:30:49.760
would interact with reading
online, where you would

00:30:49.760 --> 00:30:52.470
follow hyperlinks, for example.

00:30:52.470 --> 00:30:54.410
If you want a definition,
you wouldn't get up

00:30:54.410 --> 00:30:56.090
and go get a dictionary
you would just

00:30:56.090 --> 00:30:57.830
look right on your screen.

00:30:57.830 --> 00:31:01.660
And the difference is that
with kids, their brains

00:31:01.660 --> 00:31:03.234
really, a lot of
them can't handle

00:31:03.234 --> 00:31:04.275
that kind of distraction.

00:31:04.275 --> 00:31:06.850
And they often lose the thread
of what they're reading.

00:31:06.850 --> 00:31:11.270
But I'm getting off topic
speaking of lose the thread.

00:31:11.270 --> 00:31:17.750
Not all learning is what
happens-- thank you very much,

00:31:17.750 --> 00:31:20.360
15 minutes left.

00:31:20.360 --> 00:31:25.610
What happens in the kind of
ethereal sphere of cyberspace.

00:31:25.610 --> 00:31:28.860
Some of learning has to
do with actually talking

00:31:28.860 --> 00:31:31.830
to other people,
having an exchange,

00:31:31.830 --> 00:31:35.270
learning how to debate, learning
how to defend your views,

00:31:35.270 --> 00:31:37.910
and often what is
happening in the classroom

00:31:37.910 --> 00:31:42.600
now is that people are,
especially school boards are,

00:31:42.600 --> 00:31:44.980
following the path
of least resistance.

00:31:44.980 --> 00:31:47.590
Let's look at the
evidence of what

00:31:47.590 --> 00:31:53.100
could be predictive of academic
success other than genes.

00:31:53.100 --> 00:31:55.590
Peers, and that's where
the collaborative learning

00:31:55.590 --> 00:31:57.080
might come in.

00:31:57.080 --> 00:32:01.100
Single-sex schools-- is
this popular in California?

00:32:01.100 --> 00:32:02.439
No?

00:32:02.439 --> 00:32:03.230
That's interesting.

00:32:03.230 --> 00:32:05.280
Popular on the east coast.

00:32:05.280 --> 00:32:08.950
Class size, whether it's a
big class or a small class.

00:32:08.950 --> 00:32:12.817
Whether or not that you
have a network classroom.

00:32:12.817 --> 00:32:14.900
Whether there's a white
board, whether every child

00:32:14.900 --> 00:32:17.400
has his own screen
or her own screen.

00:32:17.400 --> 00:32:21.140
Whether there's a skilled
teacher running the show.

00:32:21.140 --> 00:32:22.990
Whether they each have
their own laptops,

00:32:22.990 --> 00:32:24.531
although most of
the time now they're

00:32:24.531 --> 00:32:25.790
tablets as opposed to laptops.

00:32:25.790 --> 00:32:27.190
I sort of always
wondered, what do they

00:32:27.190 --> 00:32:28.981
do for keyboarding when
they have a tablet?

00:32:28.981 --> 00:32:30.970
It's not very comfortable.

00:32:30.970 --> 00:32:32.232
The parents' culture.

00:32:32.232 --> 00:32:34.190
In other words, whether
they prize achievement,

00:32:34.190 --> 00:32:37.900
whether they push the children,
whether they make sure children

00:32:37.900 --> 00:32:42.890
finish a job that they started
in academic work at least.

00:32:42.890 --> 00:32:44.430
Parents' earnings.

00:32:44.430 --> 00:32:48.930
What of all of those do the
data tell us is most predictive?

00:32:48.930 --> 00:32:52.280
And when you look
at meta-analyses,

00:32:52.280 --> 00:32:53.910
essentially, when
you crunch the data

00:32:53.910 --> 00:32:58.514
from many different studies, one
of the most predictive factors

00:32:58.514 --> 00:32:59.930
of educational
outcomes-- and when

00:32:59.930 --> 00:33:01.346
I talk about
educational outcomes,

00:33:01.346 --> 00:33:07.080
I'm talking about achievement,
not things like happiness.

00:33:07.080 --> 00:33:10.550
Was the quality of the
teacher, which is interesting.

00:33:10.550 --> 00:33:15.850
Even the studies of educational
technology, the only ones that

00:33:15.850 --> 00:33:19.240
have shown really a
statistically significant

00:33:19.240 --> 00:33:22.840
difference or the ones that
have included a component

00:33:22.840 --> 00:33:25.080
of intense teacher training.

00:33:25.080 --> 00:33:27.210
So at the end, it's hard
to know whether it's

00:33:27.210 --> 00:33:29.680
the technology or the
teacher training that

00:33:29.680 --> 00:33:32.320
made a difference.

00:33:32.320 --> 00:33:33.830
One really
interesting study that

00:33:33.830 --> 00:33:39.250
was done by some economists at
Harvard of school-age children

00:33:39.250 --> 00:33:42.780
crunched a whole bunch of
data of 2.5 million children,

00:33:42.780 --> 00:33:44.530
they hadn't only
their school records,

00:33:44.530 --> 00:33:47.760
but they had their
parent's tax returns,

00:33:47.760 --> 00:33:50.760
so they could rule out income.

00:33:50.760 --> 00:33:52.670
And they also had
information on things

00:33:52.670 --> 00:33:55.520
like neighborhood,
where they lived.

00:33:55.520 --> 00:33:58.940
So they could control for many
factors that often, really very

00:33:58.940 --> 00:34:00.630
loosely controlled in the past.

00:34:00.630 --> 00:34:04.080
And what they found was that
where they had areas where

00:34:04.080 --> 00:34:08.139
a teacher boosted kids'
achievement way more than

00:34:08.139 --> 00:34:09.780
could be expected--
in other words,

00:34:09.780 --> 00:34:11.230
the teacher was an outlier.

00:34:11.230 --> 00:34:13.170
He or she was that good.

00:34:13.170 --> 00:34:15.219
If they manipulated
it and replaced

00:34:15.219 --> 00:34:17.130
a mediocre-- or
actually, let's face

00:34:17.130 --> 00:34:19.639
it, a bad teacher--
with that good teacher,

00:34:19.639 --> 00:34:22.320
he or she could boost
their achievement,

00:34:22.320 --> 00:34:25.260
but not only that had an
affect on their behavior

00:34:25.260 --> 00:34:26.830
much later in life.

00:34:26.830 --> 00:34:30.690
So one year with that
highly skilled teacher

00:34:30.690 --> 00:34:35.600
between grades three eight
made it far less likely

00:34:35.600 --> 00:34:38.780
for teenagers to become
pregnant or to make

00:34:38.780 --> 00:34:40.725
their girlfriend pregnant.

00:34:44.300 --> 00:34:47.530
It doesn't make them,
but it was associated

00:34:47.530 --> 00:34:51.130
with being more likely to go
to college, more likely to go

00:34:51.130 --> 00:34:54.880
to a good, selective
college, more

00:34:54.880 --> 00:34:57.890
likely to earn quite
a lot more as an adult

00:34:57.890 --> 00:34:59.488
over their lifespan.

00:34:59.488 --> 00:35:00.946
Did I have a comment
from somebody?

