00:35:14.390 --> 00:35:15.800
something like that.

00:35:15.800 --> 00:35:18.460
More likely to live in a good
neighborhood, which is amazing.

00:35:18.460 --> 00:35:20.540
No teenager thinks about this.

00:35:20.540 --> 00:35:26.820
So it has to do with
immeasurable effects.

00:35:26.820 --> 00:35:29.130
And more likely to
save for retirement.

00:35:29.130 --> 00:35:32.700
So is there really any
point to distinguishing

00:35:32.700 --> 00:35:39.760
between this kind of childhood--
or this kind of childhood which

00:35:39.760 --> 00:35:41.800
is what goes on right
now for many kids

00:35:41.800 --> 00:35:42.790
in their leisure time.

00:35:42.790 --> 00:35:47.760
Some shocking statistics
are that kids are spending--

00:35:47.760 --> 00:35:52.150
before they get to school, the
average is four hours a day

00:35:52.150 --> 00:35:54.120
on some sort of network device.

00:35:54.120 --> 00:35:57.120
By the time they're school
age, it's upwards of seven.

00:35:57.120 --> 00:36:00.000
In other words, they spend
more time in front of a screen

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:02.830
than they do on anything
else except sleeping.

00:36:02.830 --> 00:36:05.080
More time than
playing with friends,

00:36:05.080 --> 00:36:07.900
going to the park,
sports, school.

00:36:07.900 --> 00:36:12.040
I mean it really eclipses
all their other activities.

00:36:12.040 --> 00:36:16.545
So is there any difference
between this and this?

00:36:16.545 --> 00:36:20.190
This is a picture of
me here playing cards

00:36:20.190 --> 00:36:21.610
with my maternal grandparents.

00:36:21.610 --> 00:36:23.700
This is the one who
checked up on her friends

00:36:23.700 --> 00:36:26.860
with the black rotary phone.

00:36:26.860 --> 00:36:31.040
Is there any difference in
the types of cognitive skills

00:36:31.040 --> 00:36:33.040
that are required and the
types of social skills

00:36:33.040 --> 00:36:34.200
that are required?

00:36:34.200 --> 00:36:37.980
And I think that the research
is just now emerging.

00:36:37.980 --> 00:36:40.070
How am I doing for time?

00:36:40.070 --> 00:36:41.540
Ten minutes.

00:36:41.540 --> 00:36:46.330
There's just newly
emerging FMRI research

00:36:46.330 --> 00:36:51.360
which shows that social
interactions where there's

00:36:51.360 --> 00:36:55.210
really a give and take
between you and somebody else

00:36:55.210 --> 00:36:58.530
elicit different types
of brain activity.

00:36:58.530 --> 00:37:02.000
Essentially, the way
this research was done

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:04.520
was, Elizabeth Redcay who
was originally from Harvard

00:37:04.520 --> 00:37:07.630
but is now on the
west coast, she

00:37:07.630 --> 00:37:09.530
compared two groups of subjects.

00:37:09.530 --> 00:37:11.620
One group of
subjects, essentially,

00:37:11.620 --> 00:37:15.440
were in the scanner and
watched canned video,

00:37:15.440 --> 00:37:18.860
say, like YouTube--
that sort of idea.

00:37:18.860 --> 00:37:21.810
And the second group
had the same content

00:37:21.810 --> 00:37:24.950
but interacted about
that content socially

00:37:24.950 --> 00:37:27.140
with somebody who was
in the room with them.

00:37:27.140 --> 00:37:29.030
It was actually a
research assistant,

00:37:29.030 --> 00:37:31.780
so they had a conversation
or a discussion about it.

00:37:31.780 --> 00:37:35.220
And this subtracting
the brain activity

00:37:35.220 --> 00:37:38.140
that happened in
the canned recording

00:37:38.140 --> 00:37:43.060
scenario versus the interactive
scenario, these orange areas

00:37:43.060 --> 00:37:44.890
were the differential bits.

00:37:44.890 --> 00:37:47.880
In other words, the
brain differentially

00:37:47.880 --> 00:37:51.940
engages those regions
when interacting

00:37:51.940 --> 00:37:54.800
with a real social
partner as opposed

00:37:54.800 --> 00:38:00.420
to somebody who is just
watching and listening.

00:38:00.420 --> 00:38:04.290
And what are those regions
if you can summarize them?

00:38:04.290 --> 00:38:06.060
They have to do with
social cognition.

00:38:06.060 --> 00:38:09.070
Social cognition is
what psychologists often

00:38:09.070 --> 00:38:11.680
call theory of
mind, imagining what

00:38:11.680 --> 00:38:15.350
that other person is
thinking and feeling

00:38:15.350 --> 00:38:16.820
and intending to do next.

00:38:16.820 --> 00:38:21.100
That's social cognition, paying
attention to those social cues.

00:38:21.100 --> 00:38:22.330
Where are they looking?

00:38:22.330 --> 00:38:24.680
What does their
body language say?

00:38:24.680 --> 00:38:26.220
Are they standing
too close to you?

00:38:26.220 --> 00:38:27.210
Too far away from you?

00:38:27.210 --> 00:38:28.400
Do they look bored?

00:38:28.400 --> 00:38:31.270
Should you change your
conversation topic?

00:38:31.270 --> 00:38:33.850
And finally, something that's
really interesting to me

00:38:33.850 --> 00:38:37.530
is that elicits more activity
in the amygdala in areas

00:38:37.530 --> 00:38:41.900
that signal reward,
that feels good.

00:38:41.900 --> 00:38:44.650
You'll keep me on
track here, right?

00:38:44.650 --> 00:38:46.760
Because otherwise I'm
going to speed ahead.

00:38:46.760 --> 00:38:52.660
What are the signals that
are transmitted face-to-face?

00:38:52.660 --> 00:38:55.850
This is work by Sandy
Pentland at MIT.

00:38:55.850 --> 00:38:58.630
Mimicry and synchrony,
this is how much

00:38:58.630 --> 00:39:01.220
you echo what's going
on with somebody else

00:39:01.220 --> 00:39:02.722
when you're talking to them.

00:39:02.722 --> 00:39:04.680
So if you're in a
restaurant, you lean forward,

00:39:04.680 --> 00:39:05.710
and they lean forward.

00:39:05.710 --> 00:39:07.490
If you lean back,
they lean back.

00:39:07.490 --> 00:39:09.980
If your voice rises in
volume, does their voice

00:39:09.980 --> 00:39:10.750
rise in volume?

00:39:10.750 --> 00:39:17.000
Because essentially, we've
evolved to interact in groups.

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:19.620
So, much the way you
see birds fly together

00:39:19.620 --> 00:39:22.185
as a flock or animals
pick up behavior

00:39:22.185 --> 00:39:23.560
from another member
of the group,

00:39:23.560 --> 00:39:25.960
we do very much the
same thing because it

00:39:25.960 --> 00:39:31.590
signals to each other that
we're of one mind, essentially.

00:39:31.590 --> 00:39:35.010
The activity level, how much
you move around when you talk?

00:39:35.010 --> 00:39:38.120
The influence, how much
somebody's expressions

00:39:38.120 --> 00:39:39.990
and movements affect
the other person's?

00:39:39.990 --> 00:39:42.790
And finally,
consistency, meaning

00:39:42.790 --> 00:39:47.400
how fluid is the person,
how convincing are they,

00:39:47.400 --> 00:39:48.860
how confident are they.

00:39:48.860 --> 00:39:51.280
And when you measure
all of these things,

00:39:51.280 --> 00:39:55.480
this measures group cohesion
and confidence and productivity.

00:39:55.480 --> 00:39:57.870
And if I were you, I'd
be asking, well, how

00:39:57.870 --> 00:39:59.950
do you measure those things?

00:39:59.950 --> 00:40:02.850
With a little device that
looks like an iPhone.

00:40:02.850 --> 00:40:04.450
This is called the
sociometer and it

00:40:04.450 --> 00:40:06.570
captures those honest signals.

00:40:06.570 --> 00:40:08.960
It strips away content.

00:40:08.960 --> 00:40:12.200
So say, unlike what is done
at Google where it picks up

00:40:12.200 --> 00:40:15.650
content and aggregates
content, here it

00:40:15.650 --> 00:40:18.530
strips away content and
just looks at those signals.

00:40:18.530 --> 00:40:21.590
And using this
little device, you

00:40:21.590 --> 00:40:24.650
can tell, for example,
how negotiations are going

00:40:24.650 --> 00:40:28.710
and can predict with a
fair degree of accuracy

00:40:28.710 --> 00:40:30.410
where the negotiation will go.

00:40:30.410 --> 00:40:33.560
It predicts salary
increases of about 40%

00:40:33.560 --> 00:40:35.700
if you're more aware of
these honest signals.

00:40:38.114 --> 00:40:39.530
What's really
interesting about it

00:40:39.530 --> 00:40:43.010
is that it shows how
cohesive small groups are

00:40:43.010 --> 00:40:44.600
and the types of
signals that you

00:40:44.600 --> 00:40:47.690
need to exchange in a small
group to be productive.

00:40:47.690 --> 00:40:49.890
Whereas in larger
groups, for example,

00:40:49.890 --> 00:40:52.880
if the signals are just
logistical-- little bits

00:40:52.880 --> 00:40:54.770
and pieces of
information-- it's not

00:40:54.770 --> 00:40:57.380
really necessary to
be there in person.

00:40:57.380 --> 00:41:01.860
So if you confuse the
two, you risk losing

00:41:01.860 --> 00:41:05.050
a whole rich range of data.

00:41:05.050 --> 00:41:06.930
Now, I think I'm going
to speed ahead now

00:41:06.930 --> 00:41:10.850
and just show you one other
really cool slide where

00:41:10.850 --> 00:41:14.130
an experimenter,
essentially, manipulated

00:41:14.130 --> 00:41:17.720
facial features to find out
who looks more trustworthy.

00:41:17.720 --> 00:41:22.840
Because essentially,
in-person interactions

00:41:22.840 --> 00:41:27.890
are hugely powerful, but they're
not always used for good.

00:41:27.890 --> 00:41:31.270
And when you're together
with somebody face-to-face,

00:41:31.270 --> 00:41:33.370
not only their honest
signals influence you,

00:41:33.370 --> 00:41:37.180
but even something like their
facial features influence you.

00:41:37.180 --> 00:41:42.010
And most politicians know this,
most scam artists know this.

00:41:42.010 --> 00:41:45.680
And so as you move
along this array,

00:41:45.680 --> 00:41:47.830
I'll show you-- this
is an array that they

00:41:47.830 --> 00:41:50.440
generated of many, many
different gradations

00:41:50.440 --> 00:41:51.875
along the way.

00:41:51.875 --> 00:41:53.250
But essentially,
I'm just showing

00:41:53.250 --> 00:41:56.960
you slices where there were
like 10 gradations in between.

00:41:56.960 --> 00:42:00.700
The most honest
faces are those that

00:42:00.700 --> 00:42:04.070
are a little feminine looking.

00:42:04.070 --> 00:42:06.640
You see this person looks a
little bit feminine-looking

00:42:06.640 --> 00:42:11.010
where they're arched eyebrows
as opposed to flat eyebrows,

00:42:11.010 --> 00:42:14.960
where they have a softer,
baby-faced look and have

00:42:14.960 --> 00:42:16.730
a cheerful demeanour.

00:42:16.730 --> 00:42:19.580
And so people who
have that kind of face

00:42:19.580 --> 00:42:22.660
are more easily
elected, and they're

00:42:22.660 --> 00:42:24.820
better able to pull
the wool over our eyes.

00:42:24.820 --> 00:42:28.220
So it's not as a face-to-face
contact is always

00:42:28.220 --> 00:42:29.950
a unilateral good.

00:42:29.950 --> 00:42:35.680
For example, these guys who are
Ponzi scheme scam artists had

00:42:35.680 --> 00:42:38.080
those believable faces.

00:42:38.080 --> 00:42:41.690
Earl Jones is a
Montrealer who scammed

00:42:41.690 --> 00:42:44.750
the Anglo-Saxon
upper crust community

00:42:44.750 --> 00:42:47.230
with his baby face
and his participation

00:42:47.230 --> 00:42:48.400
in community events.

00:42:48.400 --> 00:42:50.400
He was a hockey coach.

00:42:50.400 --> 00:42:52.090
He was a church deacon.

00:42:52.090 --> 00:42:55.000
He did all sorts of great
things for the community.

00:42:55.000 --> 00:42:56.400
And people fell for him.

00:42:56.400 --> 00:42:59.180
And you can see, there's
his arched eyebrows,

00:42:59.180 --> 00:43:02.140
his baby face, his
smiling demeanor.

00:43:02.140 --> 00:43:06.320
This guy, Salah
Ezzedine, essentially,

00:43:06.320 --> 00:43:10.950
bilked the Hezbollah community
of billions of dollars--

00:43:10.950 --> 00:43:12.040
$1.2 billion.

00:43:14.820 --> 00:43:18.300
He built Hassan Nasrallah
who was the second in command

00:43:18.300 --> 00:43:19.500
of Hezbollah.

00:43:19.500 --> 00:43:22.480
And look, he's got those facial
features too-- high eyebrows.

00:43:22.480 --> 00:43:24.760
He's a little too
hairy to look feminine,

00:43:24.760 --> 00:43:28.360
but essentially, he has those
rounded features that convey,

00:43:28.360 --> 00:43:30.340
you can trust me.

00:43:30.340 --> 00:43:34.150
So why distinguish between
online and face-to-face

00:43:34.150 --> 00:43:35.780
activity?

00:43:35.780 --> 00:43:38.390
I'm going to skip past this.

00:43:38.390 --> 00:43:42.470
In a world where,
essentially, people

00:43:42.470 --> 00:43:45.960
are spending a lot of their
time online, leisure time, work

00:43:45.960 --> 00:43:52.180
time, school time, our lives
have changed in radical ways.

00:43:52.180 --> 00:43:55.740
And we're just now learning
some of the impact of this.

00:43:55.740 --> 00:43:59.820
And we used to
socialize like this.

00:43:59.820 --> 00:44:02.370
Now many of us
socialize with strangers

00:44:02.370 --> 00:44:04.850
who could be continents
away from us.

00:44:04.850 --> 00:44:10.090
For hours at a time, we spend
more than 520 billion minutes

00:44:10.090 --> 00:44:11.000
a day online.

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:12.120
And that's just the US.

00:44:12.120 --> 00:44:14.390
And it's probably
growing as I speak.

00:44:14.390 --> 00:44:18.690
So at a time when
our close networks

00:44:18.690 --> 00:44:23.550
are reducing, at a time when
loneliness has increased, when

00:44:23.550 --> 00:44:28.520
solo living has increased,
it's worth asking the question,

00:44:28.520 --> 00:44:31.800
really, what difference
does it make?

00:44:31.800 --> 00:44:34.360
Because we do know the
evidence does tell us

00:44:34.360 --> 00:44:38.820
that those with large
active in-person networks

00:44:38.820 --> 00:44:43.480
tend to live longer, happier
lives with their minds intact.

00:44:43.480 --> 00:44:45.620
And when I learned about
this, I was kind of

00:44:45.620 --> 00:44:48.290
like Meg Ryan in "When
Harry Met Sally."

00:44:48.290 --> 00:44:53.240
It was like, whatever it is,
I'll have what she's having.

00:44:53.240 --> 00:44:58.250
And that dish is what I'm
calling, village effect.

00:44:58.250 --> 00:44:59.767
Thank you.

00:44:59.767 --> 00:45:01.510
[APPLAUSE]

00:45:06.990 --> 00:45:09.390
Any questions?

00:45:09.390 --> 00:45:10.457
Yes.

00:45:10.457 --> 00:45:12.180
AUDIENCE: So, could
it be that there

00:45:12.180 --> 00:45:14.430
is some other characters
think that causes

00:45:14.430 --> 00:45:17.450
me both to socialize
and to live longer.

00:45:17.450 --> 00:45:20.620
Are there studies where they
coach people to socialize more

00:45:20.620 --> 00:45:22.517
and then they
lived a bit longer?

00:45:22.517 --> 00:45:24.100
SUSAN PINKER: There's
a couple of ways

00:45:24.100 --> 00:45:27.530
of answering that question
like what came first.

00:45:27.530 --> 00:45:34.046
And you can't, essentially,
in an ethical experiment,

00:45:34.046 --> 00:45:35.920
take two matched groups
and say, OK, you guys

00:45:35.920 --> 00:45:37.150
aren't going to
have social contact,

00:45:37.150 --> 00:45:38.691
and you guys are
going to have a lot.

00:45:38.691 --> 00:45:40.990
But you can do that with rats.

00:45:40.990 --> 00:45:43.890
And when you do that with
rats, who are social mammals,

00:45:43.890 --> 00:45:48.201
they develop 84 times the
number of malignant tumors.

00:45:48.201 --> 00:45:48.950
It's bad for them.

00:45:48.950 --> 00:45:50.340
And their behavior changes too.

00:45:50.340 --> 00:45:52.920
And we also have another natural
experiment that, actually,

00:45:52.920 --> 00:45:54.680
we're really good at in Canada.

00:45:54.680 --> 00:45:56.900
It's called solitary
confinement.

00:45:56.900 --> 00:45:59.750
And when you put prisoners
in solitary confinement,

00:45:59.750 --> 00:46:03.160
essentially, they
lose their marbles.

00:46:03.160 --> 00:46:07.610
They become ill in many ways.

00:46:07.610 --> 00:46:12.120
And there's another-- these are
mostly perspective studies that

00:46:12.120 --> 00:46:13.950
doesn't really answer
what you could answer

00:46:13.950 --> 00:46:16.180
with experimental research.

00:46:16.180 --> 00:46:21.490
But we do know one thing, which
is that a lot of the lifestyle

00:46:21.490 --> 00:46:24.620
research that has
affected all of our lives,

00:46:24.620 --> 00:46:27.480
say, for example, on
cigarette smoking.

00:46:27.480 --> 00:46:29.996
It was also
correlational research.

00:46:29.996 --> 00:46:31.870
And it's something that
has changed our lives

00:46:31.870 --> 00:46:34.170
and changed our
environment for the better.

00:46:34.170 --> 00:46:36.290
And finally, my last
comment about this

00:46:36.290 --> 00:46:39.730
is that, I'm sure a
lot of us in this room

00:46:39.730 --> 00:46:43.850
are physically active without
being Olympic athletes.

00:46:43.850 --> 00:46:46.780
We know that this
is good for us.

00:46:46.780 --> 00:46:48.650
And if we do a little
bit of, it will

00:46:48.650 --> 00:46:50.290
be good for us a little bit.

00:46:50.290 --> 00:46:53.350
And if we're great at it, it
might be marvelous for us.

00:46:53.350 --> 00:46:57.740
But we can ape the success
of other people and say,

00:46:57.740 --> 00:47:01.360
this works for that
population of 39,000 people.

00:47:01.360 --> 00:47:03.450
Maybe it'll work for me.

00:47:03.450 --> 00:47:06.780
So even without having
definitive experimental

00:47:06.780 --> 00:47:09.300
evidence, which I think is
probably coming in the future,

00:47:09.300 --> 00:47:12.516
we can still act on it before
it's too late essentially.

00:47:15.432 --> 00:47:17.990
AUDIENCE: Going along to
similar of what you just said.

00:47:17.990 --> 00:47:19.615
So there have been
studies with smoking

00:47:19.615 --> 00:47:22.490
that show if you quit
before a certain age,

00:47:22.490 --> 00:47:26.400
it has a huge impact on
your life expectancy.

00:47:26.400 --> 00:47:28.135
Have there been
similar studies done

00:47:28.135 --> 00:47:31.130
in determining if you switch
from isolation to fostering

00:47:31.130 --> 00:47:34.211
deep social networks
by a certain age it'll

00:47:34.211 --> 00:47:36.447
have an effect on your
life expectancy or not?

00:47:36.447 --> 00:47:38.280
SUSAN PINKER: That's a
really good question.

00:47:38.280 --> 00:47:41.590
I don't know of any studies
that have done that.

00:47:41.590 --> 00:47:45.410
But it would be probably
a really interesting kind

00:47:45.410 --> 00:47:46.280
of experiment.

00:47:46.280 --> 00:47:48.770
But it would have to be
a natural experiment.

00:47:48.770 --> 00:47:52.170
Because you can't
impose that on people.

00:47:52.170 --> 00:47:54.590
But it would be an
interesting experiment

00:47:54.590 --> 00:47:56.770
to do with lab animals,
say, for example.

00:47:56.770 --> 00:48:02.020
Right now, they do take
rats and separate them

00:48:02.020 --> 00:48:05.220
and have them grow up in
an isolated environment.

00:48:05.220 --> 00:48:08.160
And that has a tremendous
impact on their cognition

00:48:08.160 --> 00:48:09.390
and on their health.

00:48:09.390 --> 00:48:11.540
But I wonder, they
could probably

00:48:11.540 --> 00:48:13.920
let them grow to maturity
and then isolate them

00:48:13.920 --> 00:48:15.030
and see what happens.

00:48:15.030 --> 00:48:18.011
So you could find out if
there's a critical period.

00:48:18.011 --> 00:48:20.010
I mean I don't have the
answer to that question,

00:48:20.010 --> 00:48:22.280
but it would be really
an interesting question.

00:48:22.280 --> 00:48:28.982
I think one of the ideas that
came to me by immersing myself

00:48:28.982 --> 00:48:30.440
in this research
for a long time is

00:48:30.440 --> 00:48:37.720
I see it more as how we view
climate change research.

00:48:37.720 --> 00:48:40.560
And when I was growing up,
it was a very different

00:48:40.560 --> 00:48:41.802
environment than we have now.

00:48:41.802 --> 00:48:44.260
I mean you would drive along
the highway, open your window,

00:48:44.260 --> 00:48:46.020
and throw trash out the window.

00:48:46.020 --> 00:48:49.940
People had no idea
about the ozone layer.

00:48:49.940 --> 00:48:52.460
People were not concerned
about pollution.

00:48:52.460 --> 00:48:57.340
And we essentially were in
love with the automobile.

00:48:57.340 --> 00:49:00.309
And it has taken
us 40 years or more

00:49:00.309 --> 00:49:02.600
to realize that there have
been significant trade-offs.

00:49:02.600 --> 00:49:05.930
And we can't get back
now what we lost.

00:49:05.930 --> 00:49:08.330
In other words, our
cities have become donuts

00:49:08.330 --> 00:49:11.590
with essentially people
moving to the suburbs

00:49:11.590 --> 00:49:13.690
and we've lost
our downtown core.

00:49:13.690 --> 00:49:15.960
Many places have no sidewalks.

00:49:15.960 --> 00:49:17.710
We have a lot of air pollution.

00:49:17.710 --> 00:49:20.480
There's been an impact
on people's social lives.

00:49:20.480 --> 00:49:24.410
And I see this as a similar
kind of social experiment

00:49:24.410 --> 00:49:27.800
where we can't wait for all
the experimental research

00:49:27.800 --> 00:49:31.350
to start to examine the
impact, similar to, say,

00:49:31.350 --> 00:49:33.452
the natural food movement.

00:49:33.452 --> 00:49:35.160
A lot of people have
changed their habits

00:49:35.160 --> 00:49:37.670
without all the
evidence being in.

00:49:37.670 --> 00:49:39.470
But they don't want
to hedge their bets.

00:49:39.470 --> 00:49:42.670
They want to maybe
act conservatively.

00:49:46.220 --> 00:49:46.830
Yes.

00:49:46.830 --> 00:49:49.074
And then I'm going
to get to you.

00:49:49.074 --> 00:49:50.740
AUDIENCE: Maybe I
didn't quite catch it,

00:49:50.740 --> 00:49:53.380
but are you equating there's
a long life in happiness?

00:49:53.380 --> 00:49:55.681
Or [INAUDIBLE]?

00:49:55.681 --> 00:49:56.430
SUSAN PINKER: Yes.

00:49:56.430 --> 00:49:59.300
I'm not equating long
life and happiness at all.

00:49:59.300 --> 00:50:03.410
In other words, you
can be a miserable SOB

00:50:03.410 --> 00:50:05.640
and still live a long life.

00:50:05.640 --> 00:50:07.892
So they're two
separate variables.

00:50:07.892 --> 00:50:09.700
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:50:09.700 --> 00:50:11.750
SUSAN PINKER: Sometimes
they do, but not always.

00:50:11.750 --> 00:50:14.234
So there's research
by actually somebody

00:50:14.234 --> 00:50:15.400
who's not too far from here.

00:50:15.400 --> 00:50:17.510
He's at UC Riverside.

00:50:17.510 --> 00:50:21.400
And he more or less showed
that happiness is actually not

00:50:21.400 --> 00:50:22.770
that critical to longevity.

00:50:22.770 --> 00:50:25.320
I think his book is called
"The Longevity Project."

00:50:25.320 --> 00:50:28.210
So happiness is a great
thing for other reasons.

00:50:28.210 --> 00:50:29.911
I think it's good to be happy.

00:50:29.911 --> 00:50:31.660
And because if you're
not happy, why would

00:50:31.660 --> 00:50:35.286
you want to live a
long life, maybe?

00:50:35.286 --> 00:50:36.660
I mean I think
one of the reasons

00:50:36.660 --> 00:50:40.590
why people live long there is
there is a genetic component.

00:50:40.590 --> 00:50:43.670
But the social component makes
them want to live a long life.

00:50:43.670 --> 00:50:45.650
They're considered
part of the community.

00:50:45.650 --> 00:50:48.470
Whereas if you're isolated here
and you don't talk to anybody

00:50:48.470 --> 00:50:50.900
for weeks at a time,
maybe you wouldn't

00:50:50.900 --> 00:50:52.890
want to live that long.

00:50:52.890 --> 00:50:55.390
So I mean, they're
correlated in some way

00:50:55.390 --> 00:51:01.080
but, in terms of the better
research, does not lend them,

00:51:01.080 --> 00:51:03.100
but separates them.

